      "inputs": "The report specifies the following inputs:\n\n Exposure distribution data\n Relative risks or exposure-response relationships\n Population size by demographic category\n Baseline disease incidence/prevalence/mortality\n Life expectancy tables\n Disability weights\n Disease duration estimates\n Cause-specific mortality statistics\n Exposure prevalence estimates\n  (Page 13-20)",
      "data_sources": "National health statistics\n WHO mortality databases\n Epidemiological literature\n Exposure monitoring systems\n Population surveys\n Disease registries\n  (Page 19-22)",
      "baseline_metrics": "Mortality rates\n Incidence rates\n Prevalence rates\n DALYs\n Standard life expectancy tables\n Disability weights from Global Burden of Disease studies\n  (Page 15-18)",
      "workflow": "16. Define environmental exposure and health outcome\n\n17. Obtain exposure distribution data\n\n18. Select exposure-response relationship / RR\n\n19. Define counterfactual or theoretical minimum exposure\n\n20. Calculate attributable fraction\n\n21. Obtain baseline disease burden\n\n22. Apply attributable fraction to burden estimates\n\n23. Estimate attributable deaths, YLL, YLD, DALYs\n\n24. Conduct uncertainty analysis\n\n25. Report results by exposure and disease category\n    (Page 12-25)",
      "equations": "Population Attributable Fraction (PAF):\n\n[\nPAF = \\frac{\\sum P_i(RR_i -1)}{\\sum P_i(RR_i -1)+1}\n]\n\nWhere:\n\n (P_i) = population proportion in exposure category i\n (RR_i) = relative risk for exposure category i\n  (Page 16)\n\nAttributable burden:\n\n[\nAB = PAF \\times B\n]\n\nWhere:\n\n (AB) = attributable burden\n (B) = baseline disease burden\n  (Page 17)\n\nDALY calculation:\n\n[\nDALY = YLL + YLD\n]\n\n(Page 11)\n\nYears of Life Lost:\n\n[\nYLL = N \\times L\n]\n\nWhere:\n\n (N) = number of deaths\n (L) = standard life expectancy at age of death\n  (Page 11)\n\nYears Lived with Disability:\n\n[\nYLD = I \\times DW \\times L\n]\n\nWhere:\n\n (I) = incident cases\n (DW) = disability weight\n (L) = duration of disability\n  (Page 11)",
      "uncertainty": "The report recommends:\n\n Sensitivity analysis on RR estimates\n Uncertainty bounds for exposure estimates\n Scenario comparisons\n Monte Carlo approaches where possible\n Reporting confidence intervals and assumptions\n  (Page 23-25)",
      "quant_outputs": "The manual itself does not generate a single national burden estimate.\n    Outputs recommended include:\n\n Attributable deaths\n Attributable DALYs\n Exposure-specific burden estimates\n Disease-specific burden estimates\n Fraction attributable to environmental exposures\n  (Page 17-25)",
      "numbers": "Environmental factors estimated to contribute substantially to global disease burden\n Counterfactual exposure levels are required for PAF calculations\n Age weighting and discounting discussed as optional methodological choices\n  (Page 10-18)\n\nSpecific numeric thresholds for exposures are not universally prescribed; they depend on the exposure-risk pair.\n(Page 14-18)",
      "findings": "Environmental burden estimation can be standardized across countries.\n PAF-based methods allow quantification of environmentally attributable disease burden.\n DALYs provide a common metric for comparing heterogeneous environmental risks.\n Exposure-response evidence is central to valid burden estimation.\n  (Page 1-5, 12-25)",
      "limitations": "Data limitations in low-resource settings\n Uncertainty in exposure-response relationships\n Limited exposure monitoring in many countries\n Dependence on assumptions for counterfactual exposure levels\n Incomplete epidemiological evidence for some environmental risks\n  (Page 23-25)",
      "india_relevance": "Very high relevance because this document provides:\n\n Foundational EBOD workflow\n Standardized DALY methodology\n PAF equations directly usable in climate-health estimation\n Guidance for integrating exposure-response functions\n Framework adaptable to heat, air pollution, water, and climate-sensitive diseases in India",
      "direct_reuse": "PAF equations\n DALY/YLL/YLD framework\n Comparative risk assessment structure\n Workflow sequence for burden estimation\n Exposure-response integration logic\n Uncertainty analysis structure\n National-level burden estimation framework\n Counterfactual exposure methodology",
      "not_direct_reuse": "Exposure-specific thresholds for India climate variables are not provided\n India-specific RR functions are not included\n No climate-only disease framework\n No India-specific baseline disease datasets\n No spatiotemporal climate modeling pipeline",
      "manuscript_support": "Methods\n Burden estimation framework\n Comparative risk assessment methodology\n DALY methodology section\n Attributable fraction equations\n Uncertainty analysis\n Conceptual framework / study design\n Supplementary methodological appendix",
      "figures": "Framework diagrams for EBD estimation workflow\n Tables explaining attributable fraction calculations\n DALY component breakdown tables\n Comparative risk assessment workflow figures\n  (Page 10-20)",
      "quotes": "> \"The environmental burden of disease can be quantified using established epidemiological methods.\"\n> (Page 2)\n\n> \"The attributable fraction represents the proportional reduction in disease or mortality that would occur if exposure were reduced to an alternative ideal exposure scenario.\"\n> (Page 16)\n\n> \"DALYs combine years of life lost due to premature mortality and years lived with disability into a single metric.\"\n> (Page 11)\n\n> \"Comparative risk assessment provides a systematic framework for estimating disease burden attributable to environmental risk factors.\"\n> (Page 13)\n\n> \"Uncertainty analysis should accompany burden estimates whenever possible.\"\n> (Page 24)",
      "insights": "Foundational WHO manual for national Environmental Burden of Disease estimation.\n Provides explicit PAF, DALY, YLL, and YLD equations directly reusable in climate-health studies.\n Establishes the comparative risk assessment pipeline used in later global burden studies.\n Strong methodological fit for India-focused climate-health burden estimation workflows.\n Most reusable component is the exposure -> RR -> PAF -> DALY estimation chain with uncertainty analysis."
